stan196
2024-02-10 00:26
I've noticed that when we use synchronous message, it's contents will only contain the body, not metadata. What I mean is this: ``` ExecuteTest(t, func(transport message.TransportConfig, m message.SynchronousMessage) error { conn, err := grpc.Dial(fmt.Sprintf("127.0.0.1:%d", transport.Port), grpc.WithTransportCredentials(insecure.NewCredentials())) require.NoError(t, err) defer conn.Close() c := routeguide.NewRouteGuideClient(conn)``` here if we use protobuf plugin, we ignore the contents of the `m` param, so it's not an issue. however if we did want to use the `m` instead (idk maybe with different plugins?), it would only contain the body of the message, not metadata. I wonder if this is intentional? `pact-go` calls `pactffi_sync_message_get_response_contents_bin` to grab the bytes and populate `message.SynchronousMessage`. And in `ffi` part only grabs the `contents` field: https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-reference/blob/master/rust/pact_ffi/src/models/sync_message.rs#L358 https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-reference/blob/master/rust/pact_models/src/v4/message_parts.rs#L27 is metadata not supposed to be passed to the consumer, is it intended to only configure the provider?

christopher.tonog
2024-02-14 21:29
Hi :wave: I'm running into an issue with installing the extra libraries for pact-go (on a m2 mac): ```% pact-go install -f -d /usr/local/lib 2024/02/14 16:16:29 [INFO] set lib dir target to /usr/local/lib 2024/02/14 16:16:29 [INFO] downloading library from https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-reference/releases/download/libpact_ffi-v0.4.16/libpact_ffi-osx-aarch64-apple-darwin.dylib.gz to /usr/local/lib/libpact_ffi.dylib 2024/02/14 16:16:30 [ERROR] Your Pact library installation is out of date and we were unable to download a newer one for you: open /usr/local/lib/libpact_ffi.dylib: permission denied``` A google search led me to this github issue: https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-go/issues/239 Is it necessary to use sudo for this if I want to use the default dir? I ended up using `/tmp` to get myself unblocked but read earlier that that is not advisable. Thanks for all the help thus far!

yousafn
2024-02-14 21:36
Hey Chris, it is, as we use set lookup paths for linking the dynamic libraries https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-go/blob/901aea82975ef17de71866bef6d017f6c4d55d09/internal/native/lib.go#L6 i dont think you can set to alternate paths not listed here unless you have sip disabled and therefore able to affect dynamic library load paths with `DYLD_LIBRARY_PATH` /tmp is okay is you are aware that it may be periodically cleared, but probably not during the execution of a test shortly after installing it i believe it will also look the library in the root of your project as well as the dynamic lib search paths, which might be an option.

christopher.tonog
2024-02-14 21:57
Thanks for the reply. Curious, which other library would you link with `libpact_ffi.dylib`? I downloaded the library to the root of my current project and added it to my path (`PATH=./:$PATH`) but I don't think that worked: ```running cc failed: exit status 1 ld: library 'pact_ffi' not found```

christopher.tonog
2024-02-14 21:58
I'll work with `/tmp` for now, it may be a moot point because we may bundle all this tooling inside a docker container or abstract it with another cli

yousafn
2024-02-14 22:00
it isn?t a binary executable, it is a shared library. therefore it needs a link path for cgo or be available on the LD_LIBRARY_PATH or DYLD_*** on macos. It?ll be different on a docker container as you say. You?ll still need the library even if you _abstract it away with another cli_ - it contains pacts core functions and each of the client libraries (such as pact-go / pact-js utilise it at runtime)

yousafn
2024-02-14 22:01
anyway /tmp is fine, if your tests complain about it being missing, you can reinstall it to /tmp :+1:

christopher.tonog
2024-02-14 22:01
yep yep, sounds good and good point on the other cli comment, that might just rule that implementation out

yousafn
2024-02-14 22:04
> Curious, which other library would you link with `libpact_ffi.dylib` not quite sure on the question. this is the library containing code from the pact-reference project (written in rust, compiled into a c shared library). it is linked to pact-go via the cgo which means pact-go isn?t a pure go implementation. our other CLI tools that used to be required for v1 of pact-go, still provide functionality for interacting with a pact broker and are available standalone, via ruby, or pre installed in docker container. those are binaries, and if you download the standalone versions, they can be added to your PATH

yousafn
2024-02-14 22:05
https://docs.pact.io/diagrams/ecosystem#rust-ffi-consumers-goldberg-machine diagram of the rust ecosystem, and a link to the core library that we link to, from pact-go https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-reference/tree/master/rust/pact_ffi hope that helps a little bit :slightly_smiling_face:

christopher.tonog
2024-02-14 22:11
ah ok, yes that makes more sense to me now. That functionality, written in rust, is compiled to a c shared lib, then linked via cgo so that code can be reused essentially? Sorry if I am regurgitating what you just said, helps me understand things better :sweat_smile:

yousafn
2024-02-14 22:30
that it totally okay! It was all new to me, when I started digging in. Correct, it can be reused by any language that provides the ability to call C code, which effectively allows those languages to leverage from what was abundant, well written C code. Nowadays we can write our code in Rust and compile it down to C. Utilising it via a shared library makes process management alot easier compared to our previous state which was utilising a shared core written in Ruby, via subprocesses. There is syntactic sugar in each client language to provide idiomatic dsl?s for developers, and some languages as some extra features (such as request filters for modifying requests prior to execution)

yousafn
2024-03-07 16:50
yo dude! V3 spec introduced messages, but V4 allows for pact files to contain multiple interaction types. This wasn?t the case with V3, and it meant users were required to name either their consumers or providers differently, to distinguish between message pacts and restful pacts. v3 message consumer https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-go/blob/master/examples/consumer_v3_test.go#L92 v3 message provider https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-go/blob/master/examples/provider_test.go#L103

yousafn
2024-03-07 16:52
> ? the consumer test talks about NewMessagePactV3 which I couldn?t find, so I?ve ended up using a NewAsynchronousPact (which is in message/m4) ? like I say I got something working for this, but not 100% sure it is correct the docs look slightly out of date, so that looks to be an omission `NewMessagePactV3` doesn?t exist, looks like it is just `NewMessagePact`

matt.fellows

matt.fellows
2024-03-20 23:20
so this was asked the other day, and resulted in this issue: https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-reference/issues/399 / https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-reference/pull/405 I think you?re asking for a combination of EachKeyLike and EachValueLike type thing. Strangely it?s not currently supported, but support for combining rules has been added to the core. I don?t know how this would translate to the Pact Go API just yet, but you could create your own Matching Rule that combines the two pretty easily 1. Bump the FFI version (when this is released) 2. Create a customer https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-go/blob/master/matchers/matcher.go#L175 3. Ensure the matcher serialises a JSON value that is an array with the 2 matcher definitions you use

stan196
2024-03-20 23:23
interesting! I think we could probably just use eachValueLike, because keys are strings by default? But I didn't see `eachValueLike` in pact-go, only eachKeyLike?

matt.fellows
2024-03-20 23:33
Let me check, it?s possible it?s missing

matt.fellows
2024-03-20 23:36
Looks like it is, in fact looks like there is a bug (that matcher is unlikely to work at all)

matt.fellows
2024-03-20 23:36
see this change to the Pact JS project that corrected the original matchers there: https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-js/commit/0b2098b035a01e8c61c8165804a7eb3b0fb67c0d#diff-884c1c7cbdaafa772a7a428e0ca83ce1fc58f03972dfa0fabcb89106d6ac35f5

matt.fellows
2024-03-20 23:37
I think you?re right, in that you actually just need the `EachValueMatches` equivalent.

matt.fellows
2024-03-20 23:45
Unlikely this week, but next week likely

matt.fellows
2024-03-20 23:45
It should be fairly straightforward. If I can get you a JSON shape you could just create your own matcher and use that to test in the meantime

matt.fellows
2024-03-20 23:50
```exampleStruct := map[string]string{}{ "id": "foo", } // Create a matcher that serialises a JSON structure of this shape { 'pact:matcher:type': 'eachValue', rules: [ { 'pact:matcher:type': 'type', value: "example value", } ], value: exampleStruct, } // e.g. a very basic string-only matcher that matches type func EachValueMatches(example map[string]string) Matcher { // ... }```

rholshausen
2024-04-02 02:53
has joined #pact-go

rholshausen
2024-04-02 02:55
As to point 1.: The expressions are not evaluated recursively, so you should just inline it to get it to work. I.e. ```eachValue(matching(type, 'random'))```

rholshausen
2024-04-02 02:59
As an aside, the matching rules (and the type matcher in particular) cascade to child items, so ```eachValue(matching(type, 'random'))``` and ```matching(type, 'random')``` are equivalent when applied to repeated fields

rholshausen
2024-04-02 03:34
For point 2., I think just inline if they are simple structs. BTW, `matching(type, 'random')` for the keys makes no sense, because the keys will always be the same type. The only useful one is when you want to restrict the keys based on a regular expression.

rholshausen
2024-04-02 03:36
As to the error message above, basically it is try to tell you that the expression `"matching(type, 'random')"` is not valid because the example value `'random'` (a string value) can't be assigned to a message.

matt.fellows
2024-04-22 07:42
So I have a half-answered response to your Pact go question

matt.fellows
2024-04-22 07:42
But quick fires

matt.fellows
2024-04-22 07:44
> Now I?m specifically interested to learn about the reasons why explicit gql support has been removed from the 2.0.x release of the module (my assumption so far: cause it would be too much work to include it in the initial release? Correct, it?s just sugar over the existing DSL. I?m conflicted about inclusion of it in the Pact Go project, personally. Why should graphql get special treatment over others? Perhaps it?s best kept as a separate package? It should also possibly be best implemented properly as a https://docs.pact.io/plugins On the other hand, it?s not that much effort and would be fairly easy to maintain.

matt.fellows
2024-04-22 07:44
On balance, at this point I?d say a PR is welcome

matt.fellows
2024-04-22 07:47
As for roadmap. It?s in a fairly stable state right now, so it?s mostly bug fixes and supporting minor incremental enhancements. Generally speaking in the Pact framework writ large, the focus is getting all major languages onto: 1. The shared https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-reference/tree/master/rust/pact_ffi 2. Pact spec https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-specification/tree/version-4 (the latest) 3. https://docs.pact.io/plugins I appreciate this roadmap is not very visible, in fact, I raised this at our last https://pact-foundation.slack.com/archives/C05HCLA3C93/p1713393788489359 just last ewek.

matt.fellows
2024-04-23 11:41
You should `go get` and `go install` `http://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-go/v2`

matt.fellows
2024-04-23 11:42
The `get` will add it to your local `go.mod` and the `install` will install the `pact-go` CLI

matt.fellows
2024-04-23 11:42
Then run `pact-go install` (you may need to use `sudo` or modify the install path) if you don?t have permissions

matt.fellows
2024-04-23 11:42
If you?re using the V2 API, then you can?t use those packages from above, and should only install the non `/v2` packages

matt.fellows
2024-05-15 01:32
I think testing for errors makes sense, but probably you don?t want to test all of the possible ways of getting that error - it?s a grey area, I guess

matt.fellows
2024-05-15 01:33
> Also are we able to write table driven tests using something like a testcase struct? good question. I don?t see why you couldn?t create a struct with all of the relevant bits in it. During each test case loop you would just need to run the Pact builder

matt.fellows
2024-05-15 01:34
> WithRequestPathMatcher(?POST?, Regex(?/postData?, ?/postData?)). so the question is - do you actually need a regex here? Is your API client going to be sending it to a different path or will it always be `/postData`? Based on the regex, it?s not changing. So you don?t need a regex is what I?m saying

matt.fellows
2024-05-15 01:35
> b.BodyMatch(interface{}). this needs to be a struct that has `pact` struct tags on it (see docs), or it needs to be something like `map[string]interface{}` with the fields you want to match

matt.fellows
2024-05-15 01:36
> Header(?Content-Type?, Term(?application/json?, `application\/json`)). again, you?re using a regex, but the regex matches an exact string > Header(?x-request-context?, Like(`?{\?geolocation\?:{\?metadata\?: \?test\?}}?`)) is this really a header? Also this just says ?this header just needs to be a string? - is that what you want?

saif.farooqui
2024-05-15 04:44
? path will always be /postData ? response body is big so I have used map[string]interface ? will not use regex for header content-type ? the header key "x-request-context" its value is object which has 30 keys-value pairs.

matt.fellows
2024-05-15 06:05
You still need to match the response structure though, otherwise any response will pass which is not very helpful. Can you show me how you plan on testing the body?

matt.fellows
2024-05-15 06:43
thanks, you need to match the body either using: ? the `BodyMatch` function, which takes a struct with `pact` struct tags: https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-go/blob/master/docs/consumer.md#auto-generate-matchers-from-struct-tags ? or manually creating the matchers (more common): https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-go/blob/master/docs/consumer.md#nesting-matchers

matt.fellows
2024-05-15 06:44
You can follow the examples to get an idea: https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-go/blob/master/examples/consumer_v2_test.go#L69

matt.fellows
2024-07-04 01:48
> ?response?: { > ?request? : { Is that correct? I.e. in the response you?re expecting a protobuf structure with a top key called `request`? Also it seems like you want a request/response style interaction, so `AsynchronousMessage` is the incorrect type to use - that?s for a unidirectional message. You should use the `SynchronousMessage` type

matt.fellows
2024-07-04 01:50
> On a similar note, is there a good resource to learn about how one would help specify what the pact-server should return to a client in a consumer test? In the gRPC example, it wasn?t exactly clear what was instructing the server to return ?Big Tree?. Big tree is just a value for type of geometric feature in the example, but the data could be anything that makes sense in your domain. Usually it would come from a database or downstream system (stubbed in the case of a Pact test) > I?ve read there are states, but I?m not sure how to set the server to a given state (.e.g,. ?feature ?Big Tree? exists?). Provider states are the pre-conditions required for a test to run. The implementation (i.e. how you setup for that state) is dependent on your application circumstances, but is often just seeding a database entry

matt.fellows
2024-07-04 01:50
see https://docs.pact.io/getting_started/provider_states and https://docs.pact.io/provider/using_provider_states_effectively

nice! I appreciate the interface isn?t type safe / obvious, and this can make it harder to debug. Your feedback at the end of this would be great, as we look at a ?v2.0? of the plugin ecosystem

ancyaziz
2024-07-24 06:02
Hi, I have a question. some of the consumer pacts are not verified by my provider, Everything at the bottom are getting verified, but the top few are not getting verified. Anyone has seen this before or know how to resolve this? I recently updated pact to v4. Thanks in advance!

matt.fellows
2024-07-24 06:23
The obvious question is?how are you running verifications? My guess is, your provider verification job isn?t selecting them (see http://docs.pact.io/selectors). And you don?t have webhooks setup to validate the specific pacts (see http://docs.pact.io/webhooks)

matt.fellows
2024-07-24 06:23
I?d recommend doing the CI/CD workshop (see howtolearn :point_down: )

2024-07-24 06:23
Here are a number of useful hands-on labs that teach all of the key concepts: https://docs.pactflow.io/docs/workshops and https://docs.pact.io/implementation_guides/workshops

ancyaziz
2024-07-24 06:29
Thank you Matt for the quick response! I was using the selector tag before, but with new consumer.NewV4Pact(consumer.MockHTTPProviderConfig), which selectors are available to use?

matt.fellows
2024-07-24 07:04
that?s the consumer side. You don?t specify selectors there

matt.fellows
2024-07-24 07:04
The provider specifies the selectors during verification - they are the pacts to ?select? for verification

ancyaziz
2024-07-24 07:05
okay, thank you Matt! I will give it a try.

matt.fellows
2024-07-24 07:05
you should have two provider builds - one for building the provider, and one for verifying a single pact that was passed in the webhook (see the material above)

matt.fellows
2024-08-05 21:48
V2 doesn't use the CLI tools at test time, so I suspect you have an old package dependency reference

matt.fellows
2024-08-05 21:49
The setup flag is passed into the closure by the framework. The state handler will fire before and after the test runs to give you an opportunity to setup and tear down

yousafn
2024-10-24 23:28
The pact url is traditionally a path to a specific version, rather than the latest pact for a given consumer/provider pair. That combination would normally be handled by consumer version selectors, in which you could for example set the `latest` consumer version selector to true, which would give you what you are trying to achieve with the URL, but dynamically working out what consumers there are, from the pact broker itself. example go provider test https://github.com/pactflow/example-provider-golang/blob/d79911b22891a37f569148174c7a2c2dcf3c64bf/user_service_test.go#L41-L54 docs on consumer version selectors https://docs.pact.io/pact_broker/advanced_topics/consumer_version_selectors#properties

yousafn
2024-11-08 16:08
pact-go uses cgo to interop with a shared library written in rust and compiled. you must have the libraries on your machine, as the pact-go dsl is a wrapper around the functionality provided by it. https://docs.pact.io/diagrams/ecosystem#rust-ffi-consumers-goldberg-machine Which platform are you running on?

yousafn
2024-11-08 16:09
the pact-go cli tool is a convenience helper for go users to manage downloading and installing the library in the correct place and on macos setting required properties in the binary

The way I understand it when running the validation, the pact is read from the broker, the requests defined against it are run against this proxy, and the proxy dispatches the request to the actual running service, right?

yousafn
2024-11-21 18:14
correct, the proxy isn?t strictly necessary, but it allows for ? request filters (modifying the inflight request before it hits your provider) ? pre/post test suite hooks (and possibly pre/post interaction, although would need to confirm in pact-go impl) Also proxies are provided for ? State handlers ? Message handlers Allowing you to map them to Go code. Under the hood, the are just endpoints which accept post requests with json blobs, which the language author have provided some DSL magic, to make it feel like its a more native experience.

yousafn
2024-11-25 23:40
Pact requires CGO, so it won't work with CGO_ENABLED=0 on any platform. Alpine isn't supported, and the code warns when it notes it is running on a musl based platform. I've raised a tracking issue here https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-go/issues/453 along with a pull request, but I can't get a clean run. CGO alpine support isn't as good, or as well tested as gnu, and seems to suffer regressions from looking through the mailing lists. You could try and load the pact shared library yourself from the pact-ref website, for musl https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-reference/releases/download/libpact_ffi-v0.4.23/libpact_ffi-linux-aarch64-musl.so.gz if you are running aarch64

marcus
2024-11-26 02:13
Thanks. I?ll try loading the library directly tomorrow to see if it works. A follow-up question, this is only required in `pact-go` V2, right?

yousafn
2024-11-26 02:21
v1 doesn?t need cgo and uses the pact ruby standalone for the cli tools. alpine guidance here to run those binaries https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-ruby-standalone/wiki/Using-the-pact-ruby-standalone-with-Alpine-Linux-Docker an alternative down the line for users who cant use cgo or the shared libraries would be to rework the v1 interface to use the new rust based cli tools, however they wont be a drop in replacement and its probably not something we would spend time on as maintainers but there would be nothing stopping anyone from doing so.

yousafn
2024-11-26 02:25
i put forward a proposal for a non cgo based alternative https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-go/issues/452 but it also doesnt work in alpine which suggests there is some tomfoolery going on. ( segfaults in the same ci tests ) your mileage may vary with the alpine shared libs. hopefully they are okay. i?m potentially okay allowing for the install of the musl binaries in the installer despite the fact we cant get the ci tests passing, and maybe by it being accessible to users might get them curious to resolve any alpine specific issues they see

xuyunzhao
2024-12-02 23:58
Hello everyone! I'm new to contract testing. I've already set up a simple contract testing framework, but I have some questions in practice. I have a test related to time. For example, a certain API will return different values during specific time periods. For instance, it will return `{a: "aaa"}` on December 5th, `{b: "bbb"}` on the 8th, and `{a: "ccc"}` on the 9th. I'd like to know: ? Do I need to include the above logics in the contract testing? Should all functional changes be included or only when the structure changes from `a` to `b`? ? How should such conditional changes that return different results be handled in contract testing? Do I need to mock the server side? If mock is needed, should it be done at a relatively earlier position, like directly mocking in the Controller, or at a relatively later position, such as inserting several test data into the database in the dev environment? And how should the situation related to time be dealt with? ? Where can I learn the knowledge about this kind of writing practice? thanks

matt.fellows
2024-12-03 04:18
Following on from https://pact-foundation.slack.com/archives/C5F4KFKR8/p1733197606572679

matt.fellows
2024-12-03 04:19
> Do I need to include the above logics in the contract testing? Should all functional changes be included or only when the structure changes from `a` to `b`? no, only the shape as shown above. Testing the behaviour is a functional test > How should such conditional changes that return different results be handled in contract testing? Do I need to mock the server side? If mock is needed, should it be done at a relatively earlier position, like directly mocking in the Controller, or at a relatively later position, such as inserting several test data into the database in the dev environment? And how should the situation related to time be dealt with? 1. Use provider states 2. yes, mocking is fine (see also https://docs.pact.io/provider#stub-calls-to-downstream-systems) a. The answer depends a lot on context, but usually I would mock where it is most practical to do so, but *does not* impact the validity of the contract test itself (e.g. for an extremely absurd example, simply replacing the entire response with a JSON that satisfies the test is not testing your real code, but will make the tests pass) > Where can I learn the knowledge about this kind of writing practice? https://docs.pact.io/consumer

Hello everyone, I'm encountering an issue with our Pact consumer tests using pact-go v2.0.1 and go 1.21.13. When sending the request, we're using Body(contentType, content), where contentType is generated by the FormDataContentType() method from multipart.Writer. Here?s how the interaction is defined: ```WithRequest(http.MethodPost, url, func(b *consumer.V4RequestBuilder) { b.Body(contentType, content) }).``` Error: ```Mismatch with header 'Content-Type': Expected header 'Content-Type' to have value 'multipart/form-data;boundary=a76648f32eda23feef43a81954d35cbd782294c16f488baef7acbda53e32' but was 'multipart/form-data; boundary=325ce599ed0e830d149d04fa6be3c58835aa1bb7f8d31cb22d2514534999'``` is there a way to use the Body method without specifying a contentType to avoid boundary mismatches? Thanks.

rholshausen
2025-01-07 03:08
You're getting very confused. What I think you mean to say is that the body and content type header have to have the same boundary marker, and the content type header needs to have a matcher setup because on the other side, the boundary marker will be different.

matt.fellows
2025-01-07 03:12
> What I think you mean to say is that the body and content type header have to have the same boundary marker, yes. I was expecting to be able to use a _request_ matcher to loosen the restriction on them having to match. I?m not worried about the provider side just yet. I?m only worried about getting the consumer test to pass. I?ll get to that next

rholshausen
2025-01-07 03:13
No, they have to be exactly the same boundary marker, otherwise it won't be a valid muti-part

rholshausen
2025-01-07 03:14
All the multi-part implements take the boundary marker from the content type header, and then split the body into parts using that value. If they are different, it won't work.

matt.fellows
2025-01-07 03:15
ok. So the regex above is only really relevant if the multipart is a response (rather than a request)? Because on the request, the boundary has to be correct

rholshausen
2025-01-07 03:16
Yes, it is for validating the other side, because the marker is always randomly generated

rholshausen
2025-01-07 03:18
Well, that's not true. A POST request in a consumer test can end up with a different boundary marker. I.e., a test that says I will receive a POST with a multi-part body, and then uses a library to generate a request to the mock server, the boundaries will be different unless in the test you force the same value.

matt.fellows
2025-01-07 03:20

rholshausen
2025-01-07 03:21
The Pact interaction and the actual request will have different boundary markers, so the regex has to be set on the content type.

And those align with (or is taken from??) what the `@Test` sends (i.e. what https://github.com/pact-foundation/pact-jvm/blob/master/consumer/junit5/src/test/java/au/com/dius/pact/consumer/junit5/MultipartRequestTest.java#L50-L55 sends)? rholshausen
2025-01-07 03:32
No, they align with what the Pact interaction setup. What the test sends will be different. I.e. you define an interaction with boundary `A`, and then the test creates a request with boundary `B`. `A` is what gets put in the Pact file.

2025-01-07 04:37
OK for @kevser.sirca when you return to this epic thread. TL;DR - for now, try to ensure the boundary in the headers are correct in both the test setup _and_ the HTTP client call. example test: ```func TestMultipart(t *testing.T) { log.SetLogLevel("TRACE") mockProvider, err := consumer.NewV2Pact(consumer.MockHTTPProviderConfig{ Consumer: "PactGoV2Consumer", Provider: "V2Provider", Host: "127.0.0.1", }) assert.NoError(t, err) // Set up our expected interactions. mockProvider. AddInteraction(). UponReceiving("A multipart request"). WithRequestPathMatcher("POST", S("/formpost"), func(b *consumer.V2RequestBuilder) { var buf bytes.Buffer content := multipart.NewWriter(&buf) content.SetBoundary("abcd") content.WriteField("baz", "bat") content.Close() b.Body(fmt.Sprintf("multipart/form-data;boundary=%s", content.Boundary()), buf.Bytes()) }). WillRespondWith(200). ExecuteTest(t, func(config consumer.MockServerConfig) error { client := &http.Client{} var buf bytes.Buffer content := multipart.NewWriter(&buf) content.SetBoundary("abcd") content.WriteField("baz", "bat") content.Close() req := &http.Request{ Method: "POST", URL: &url.URL{ Host: fmt.Sprintf("%s:%d", "localhost", config.Port), Scheme: "http", Path: "/formpost", }, Body: io.NopCloser(&buf), Header: make(http.Header), } req.Header.Set("Content-Type", fmt.Sprintf("multipart/form-data;boundary=%s", content.Boundary())) _, err := http://client.Do(req) return err }) assert.NoError(t, err)```

matt.fellows
2025-01-28 04:10
sorry, it was a long weekend here in Australia. Glad you figured it out - what was it? You would have discovered that adding the `.so` file to `PATH` will have no effect, as that is only relevant to executables. What needs to happen is the library is on the dynamic loading path (`LD_LIBRARY_PATH` or `DYLD?` on osx)

yousafn
2025-03-07 11:15
The pact_mock-service you?ve linked to only supports up to version 2.0 and has been superseded by pact_mock_server_cli written in rust https://docs.pact.io/implementation_guides/overview#cli-tooling most pact-go users will not use the cli directly, as pact-go v2 interacts with the mock server, via a shared library. You?ve posted in pact-go chat, are you using the pact_mock-service via pact-go v1? or just standalone? Also naming wise, it is Pact, not PACT. :)

I want to use Pact to verify that the GraphQL requests are being sent correctly. Initially, I set up the mock provider using the DSL provided by Pact-Go and configured a test container running the Krakend service to interact with the mock provider. To address this, I rewrote the test to use another test container running the mock service and set up a Docker network to enable communication between the containers in the CI/CD environment. While this approach worked, the mock service is based on an older version of Pact, and I?d like to use the latest version. I?ll try to replace the mock-server image with pact_mock_server_cli to see if I can get it working.

yevhen.nosulko
2025-05-02 09:45
hello lovely people. I am having a problem with pact-go Provider verification test where it cannot read the provider states from a contract json generated by pact-jvm. There is a mismatch in how the contract JSON is generated by pact-jvm and pact-go. Let me explain a bit more. We have a Consumer test written in Java with pact-jvm, snippet below: ```@Pact(provider = PROVIDER, consumer = CONSUMER) public RequestResponsePact operationalHealth(PactDslWithProvider builder) { return builder .given("IFE functionalHealth is Operational") .uponReceiving("A request for IFE availability status Operational") ... ... ...``` this will generate a contract where provider state is defined as an Array of Strings: ``` "interactions": [ { "description": "A request for IFE availability status Operational", "providerStates": [ { "name": "IFE functionalHealth is Operational" } ],``` on the provider side we have a Provider test written in Golang with pact-go, snippet as follows: ```StateHandlers: models.StateHandlers{ "IFE functionalHealth is Operational": func(setup bool, ps models.ProviderState) (models.ProviderStateResponse, error) { ... ... ...``` and the problem is when I run this test it doesn't seem to read the provider states at all because when I tried to pusposely break it it was still passing. I went ahead and created a similar consumer test in Golang, like this: ``` mockProvider. AddInteraction(). Given("IFE functionalHealth is Operational"). UponReceiving("A request for IFE availability status Operational"). ... ... ... ...``` after running this test I got the contract JSON where provider state is defined as String: ``` "interactions": [ { "description": "A request for IFE availability status Operational", "providerState": "IFE functionalHealth is Operational",``` this contract is then consumed and parsed correctly by provider test because when I try to break it I see a corresponding provider state failing. Are you guys aware of similar issues? If so how do I go about addressing it? Thank you in advance.

yousafn
2025-05-02 10:24
providerState defined as a string was part of the pact v2.0 specification. in pact v3.0+ it is stored as an array under `providerStates` which each array entry object supporting `name` and `params` pact-go allows you to create v2/v3/v4 specification pacts but they use different constructors, I assume you have used the v2 interface for your similar golang consumer test > and the problem is when I run this test it doesn?t seem to read the provider states at all because when I tried to pusposely break it it was still passing More detail would be required for this, in order to help. Is it possible to see the code for provider test/verifier on the golang side > in relation to the logs, I?ll try to figure out how to output the, cause at the moment I don?t see much logs if you run with `go test -v` do you get more verbose logs?

matt.fellows
2025-05-02 11:19
Yeah, on the provider side the verifier should handle whatever version of pact comes its way. I think the logs would be helpful, if you can just redact anything sensitive don?t worry if it?s too noisey

yevhen.nosulko
2025-05-02 13:13
ok, after endless troubleshooting it looks like it's not the `StateHandlers` being the culprit but the `matchingRules` in the contract :disappointed:. So @matt.fellows @yousafn if you are still interested in getting to the bottom of it I'm attaching the example of the pact contract (generated by pact-jvm) here and my provider test in golang

yevhen.nosulko
2025-05-02 13:19
basically what I found is as soon as `matchingRules` is added to the contract JSON the provider test is always passing even if the response body from the provider app doesn't match. The way I tried to break it is by changing the body in the contract to something different then the provider app returns, for example: ``` "body": { "someProperty": "somethingDoneeeeeeeeee" }, ``` note multiple "eeeeeee" at the end. With this setup the test still passes (false positive) if the `matchingRules` is in the contract but as soon as I delete it from the contract the test is correctly failing

yevhen.nosulko
2025-05-02 13:21
this matcher is in the contract because they added it in the java consumer test like so: ```.willRespondWith() .status(200) .headers(new HashMap<String, String>() {{ put("Content-Type", "application/json"); }}) .body(new PactDslJsonBody() .stringType("someProperty", "somethingDone")) .toPact();```

yousafn
2025-05-02 14:16
your matching rule is type, and the type is inferred from the example value. here a string. also as defined in the consumer test dsl. that means you care about someProperty with any string value. if you change the type returned by the provider, to integer for example, it will fail

yevhen.nosulko
2025-05-02 14:55
I thought apart from checking what''s in the matching rule it would still do a regular body match to make sure the actual value corresponds to the expected, should there be an additional matching rule in that case?

hwang
2025-05-02 19:19
has joined #pact-go

matt.fellows
2025-05-05 04:26
> I thought apart from checking what??s in the matching rule it would still do a regular body match to make sure the actual value corresponds to the expected, should there be an additional matching rule in that case? not always. Most of the time, the ?shape? is what you care about. If you care about exact values _don?t use a matcher._ Some guides on best practices for consumer tests: https://docs.pact.io/consumer

yevhen.nosulko
2025-05-06 09:31
fair enough. Thank you so much @matt.fellows and @yousafn for sacrificing your precious time to help me out with my issue. I'm glad the issue turned out to be user error.

matt.fellows
2025-05-06 09:35
Not at all, but appreciate the lovely message :pray:

yousafn
2025-05-06 13:49
our pleasure @yevhen.nosulko, always here and if you want to share your Pact experiences with the world, we can help provide the platform :)

aofadero
2025-08-28 15:47
Hey everyone, my team is looking start adding consumer driven contract tests as part of the tools we use with testing our microservices and one of the things that we want to do as a start is refactor the way setup our services. By this I mean currently in the `main.go` file for a service, there is a lot of setup (e.g grpc server, db connections, config refs) and we would like to abstract this to a service file so that it's no longer done in `main.go`. Is this the right approach or are there better established patterns to use?

yousafn
2025-08-28 18:20
that sounds sensible to me. your main.go can pull in your deps which are stored in sep files. i?m not sure if dependency injection in a preferred approach in golang. we would for example instantiate a single db client and pass it into our any classes that needed access to the db. that way we could easily pass in a mock or switch out the underlying impl to something else

aofadero
2025-08-28 18:41
Hey @yousafn thanks for your feedback. That's what we're trying to so that we can have the ability to switch out the underlying implementation if/when necessary. I was just wondering if there are other recommended approaches other than that
